From this finding, it would seem that counselling services provided by the courts are necessary because it would assist the fathers to initiate and maintain relationships with the child. Those fathers who report having a relationship with their child are not afraid to challenge or talk back to the mothers; this is most of the time seen as disrespectful. In contrast to this situation, some of the fathers who do not have current access to their child, stated that talking back to the mother is quite normative because mothers tend to deny fathers access to the child.
These fathers also indicated some fear being intimidated which stop them from challenging the mother. This anger and resentment leads these fathers to allow the mothers to control the child and prevent fathers from having relationships.
It appears that fathers who do not see their children face challenges similar to the problems experienced by the fathers who see their children on occasion. For example, some of these fathers stated that their situations further aggravate their frustrations for the other fathers who have difficulty establishing relationships with their children. These fathers also find themselves involved in unhealthy conflict because they do not see the child. They experience challenges such as helpless feelings because the mothers control the child. Others reported their challenges of negative stress feelings because of conflicting feelings due to the lack of contact with their child.
